The configuration `native_transport_max_frame_size_in_mb` is related to the maximum frame size allowed in the native transport protocol. This configuration is crucial in preventing overly large messages from being processed, which could potentially lead to performance issues or even crashes.

#### Relevant Code Segments

The following code segments are directly related to the configuration `native_transport_max_frame_size_in_mb`:

```java
public static class Decoder extends ByteToMessageDecoder {
    private static final int MAX_TOTAL_LENGTH = DatabaseDescriptor.getNativeTransportMaxFrameSize();

    // ...

    @VisibleForTesting
    Envelope decode(ByteBuf buffer) {
        // ...

        long totalLength = bodyLength + Header.LENGTH;
        if (totalLength > MAX_TOTAL_LENGTH) {
            // Enter the discard mode and discard everything received so far.
            discardingTooLongMessage = true;
            tooLongStreamId = streamId;
            tooLongTotalLength = totalLength;
            bytesToDiscard = discard(buffer, totalLength);
            if (bytesToDiscard <= 0)
                fail();
            return null;
        }

        // ...
    }

    private void fail() {
        // Reset to the initial state and throw the exception
        long tooLongTotalLength = this.tooLongTotalLength;
        this.tooLongTotalLength = 0;
        discardingTooLongMessage = false;
        String msg = String.format("Request is too big: length %d exceeds maximum allowed length %d.", tooLongTotalLength, MAX_TOTAL_LENGTH);
        throw ErrorMessage.wrap(new InvalidRequestException(msg), tooLongStreamId);
    }
}
```

In this code, `MAX_TOTAL_LENGTH` is set to the value of `native_transport_max_frame_size_in_mb` retrieved from `DatabaseDescriptor.getNativeTransportMaxFrameSize()`. This value is used to check if the total length of the message exceeds the maximum allowed length. If it does, the message is discarded, and an exception is thrown.

#### Key Configuration Interaction

The key interaction with the `native_transport_max_frame_size_in_mb` configuration occurs in the `decode` method of the `Decoder` class, where the total length of the message is checked against the maximum allowed length (`MAX_TOTAL_LENGTH`). This check prevents overly large messages from being processed and helps maintain the performance and stability of the system.

By focusing on this specific configuration, the code ensures that the system can handle messages of varying sizes while preventing potential issues caused by excessively large messages.

